%eg
  Nature et calcul de $\int_{0}^{1}\frac{\ln(1-x^{2})}{x^{2}}\dd x$.

  ---

  La fonction $f: \applic{\oo{0,1}}{\R}{x}{\frac{\le(1-x^{2})}{x^{2}}}$ est continue sur $\oo{0,1}$. En effet,
  $$
    f(x) \usim{x\to 0^{+}} \frac{-x^{2}}{x^{2}} = -1
  $$
  donc $\lim_{x\to 0^{+}}f(x) = -1$ donc $f$ est prolongeable par continuité sur $\co{0,1}$.
  Soit $0 < \varepsilon < x < 1$.
  $$
    \int_{\varepsilon}^{x}\frac{\ln(1-t^{2})}{t^{2}}\dd t = \left[- \frac{\ln(1-t^{2})}{t}\right]_{\varepsilon}^{x} - \int_{c}^{x}\frac{2t}{t(1-t^{2})}\dd t = -\frac{\ln(1-x^{2})}{x} + \frac{\ln(1-\varepsilon^{2})}{\varepsilon} - \int_{\varepsilon}^{x}\frac{2}{1-t^{2}}\dd t
  $$
  or $\int_{\varepsilon}^{x}\frac{2 \dd t}{1-t^{2}} = \int_{\varepsilon}^{x}\left(\frac{1}{1-t} + \frac{1}{1+t}\right)$ donc
  $$
    \int_{\varepsilon}^{x}\frac{\ln(1-t^{2})}{t^{2}}\dd t = -\frac{\ln(1-x^{2})}{x} + \frac{\ln(1-\varepsilon^{2})}{\varepsilon} - \left[\ln \abs{1+t} - \ln \abs{1-t}\right] = -\frac{\ln(1-x^{2})}{x} + \frac{\ln(1-\varepsilon^{2})}{\varepsilon} - \ln \abs{\frac{1+x}{1-x}} + \ln \abs{\frac{1+\varepsilon}{1-\varepsilon}}
  $$
  donc en passant à la limite sur $\varepsilon$ en 0 :
  $$
    \int_{0}^{x}\frac{\ln(1-t^{2})}{t^{2}}\dd t = -\frac{\ln(1-x^{2})}{x} - \ln \abs{\frac{1+x}{1-x}}
  $$
  d’où en utilisant $\frac{\ln(1-\varepsilon^{2})}{\varepsilon}\usim{\varepsilon\to 0}\frac{-\varepsilon^{2}}{\varepsilon} = -\varepsilon$,
  $$
    \begin{align*}
      \int_{0}^{x}\frac{\ln(1-t^{2})}{t^{2}}\dd t &= -\frac{\ln(1+x)}{x} - \ln(1+x) - \frac{\ln(1-x)}{x} + \ln(1-x)\\
      &=-(1+\frac{1}{x})\ln(1+x) + \ln(1-x)(1-\frac{1}{x})\\
      &=- \left(1+\frac{1}{x}\right)\ln(1+x) - \frac{(1-x)\ln(1-x)}{x}
    \end{align*}
  $$
  d’où
  $$
    \int_{0}^{x}\frac{\ln(1-t^{2})}{t^{2}}\dd t \arrowlim{x\to 1} -2\ln 2
  $$
  donc $\int_{0}^{1}\frac{\ln(1-x^{2})}{x^{2}}\dd x$ est convergente et
  $$
    \int_{0}^{1}\frac{\ln(1-x^{2})}{x^{2}}\dd x = -2\ln 2
  $$
